The mosque's name, "Sunehri," meaning "golden," aptly describes its beauty, with its golden-hued domes that shimmer under the sunlight. The facade is adorned with ornate arches and floral motifs, showcasing exquisite craftsmanship from that era.

However, while the mosque stands as a testament to history, its maintenance and preservation need continuous attention to ensure its splendor endures for future generations to admire. Visitors should also be mindful of the local customs and dress modestly when visiting this revered place of worship.

The Sunehri Masjid, or Golden Mosque, was built in 1721-1722 by Roshan-ud-Daula, a Mughal amir. The mosque was dedicated to Roshan-ud-Daula's spiritual mentor, Shah Bhik. The mosque's name comes from its gilt-covered domes and peaks.
The mosque is located near Chandni Chowk in Old Delhi. It's still used for religious purposes.
The mosque's history includes:
In 1737, Nadir Shah displayed his unsheathed sword from the mosque's ramparts as a signal to commence the slaughter.
In 1739, the Persian Nadir Shah invaded Delhi.
The mosque's location has been coveted by numerous empires and dynasties, including the ancient ruler of the Kuru Empire and the British Raj.
There's also a Sunehri Masjid in Lahore. It was built in 1753 by Nawab Bukhari Khan, who was Lahore's deputy governor during the reign of Muhammad Shah.

Udham Bai later known as Qudsia Begum was first introduced as a dancer in Mughal Mughal court and soon she won everyone's heart including the 13th Mughal Emperor, Muhammad Shah. She was married to Muhammad Shah they both had a son Ahmad Shah Bahadur who became the 14th Mughal Emperor in 1748 after the death of his father. As a widow, she took the title, Qudsia Begum. She was an administrator and served as de facto regent of India from 1748 to 1754.

Qudsia Begum was known for her enthusiasm and keen interest in architecture best known for the palace and garden complex, Qudsia Bagh on the banks of Yamuna, although that one no longer exists.

In 1750-51, She constructed a mosque called Sunehri Masjid also known as The Golden Mosque for Nawab Bahadur Javed Khan, a chief eunuch of the royal household.

The Sunehri Masjid is located outside the Delhi Gate of the Red Fort, Delhi. It's a three-domed mosque, which was originally gilt with copper and other parts with a light salmon-colored stone from which it derives its name. The mosque has a main prayer hall and two tall tall minarets on the front and two small ones at the back. The elevated foundation upon which the mosque is based has a beautiful entrance gate.

In 1852, Bahadur Shah II repaired the mosque by replacing the damaged copper plates with sandstone.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Lal Qila, also known as the Red Fort, is an iconic historical monument located in Old Delhi, India. It holds immense historical and cultural significance as it was the main residence of Mughal emperors for nearly two centuries, from 1639 to 1857.

The Red Fort, designed by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan, is an architectural marvel and an excellent example of Mughal architecture. It gets its name from the striking red sandstone used in its construction, giving it a distinctive appearance. The fort complex is surrounded by massive walls and features impressive gates, pavilions, and beautiful gardens.

Lal Qila is renowned for its rich history and association with India's struggle for independence. It was here that the Indian National Flag was hoisted for the first time on August 15, 1947, marking India's independence from British colonial rule.

Today, the Red Fort is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a popular tourist attraction. Every year, on India's Independence Day, the Prime Minister hoists the national flag and delivers a speech from the Red Fort's ramparts. The fort serves as a symbol of India's sovereignty and its historical legacy, making it a must-visit destination for those interested in India's history and culture.

featured_reviews.review_id:
MONTH OF VISIT : ?  I visited this area near Jama Masjid in May when Ramzan was going on and in day time ( 2-3pm)

REASON OF VISIT : ? I went there because I wanted to try delicious food and I consider no better time than Ramzan to visit this place.

AREA COVERED : ? I covered lane opposite to Gate No. 1

FOOD : Since I am vegetarian I had very less option to choose and thus made sure to try all that comes under my category

1) Sharbat E Mohabbat : This is the best thing and was my very reason of coming here. I thankfully get to try this. This drink is best summer drink which I think can come into all cities. This is a mixture of Roohafza, water, milk and watermelon.

Price : Rs. 70

2) Shrimal : The second dish which I have tried on this lane was shrimal which has huge variety from pistachio to almond.

Price : Rs 70-100

3) Kiwi and Dragon Fruit Plate : Just when you are roaming around here you will surely feel the need of keep hydrating yourself and KIWI and DRAGON FRUIT at just Rs. 10 are something which you should not afford to miss.

4) Dates : Rest you will see many vendors of dates which has dry as well as packed dates.
